                <note rend="inline" type="source">356.115/12–2644: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Huddle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-26T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 26, 1944—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 13, 1945—5 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–876. American Interests—Netherlands—Germany. Legation’s airmail 9052 August
                        18.<note n="13" xml:id="d764fn13">Not printed.</note> Foreign Office note
                    December 20 states Swiss Legation Berlin received early in December note dated
                    October 19 from German Foreign Office reading in part in translation as follows:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The Foreign Office has ordered that personal property of British and
                            American nationals, as well as of nationals of other countries whose
                            interests are protected by Switzerland, will not be claimed for the use
                            of German people who have suffered damage through bombardment.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huddle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
